Ok, so my opinion is:
This movie was soooooooo messed up.
(Spoiler alert from the book)

Just starting w the fact that things that happened in the first movie actually only happened in the second book, like them getting together finally AND in the books there's a really big mess with the video. Like, LJ gets bullied, cyberbullied, hated, etc. And that was like 80% cut of the movies. As I said, they only get together in the second book, and the video thing only happens in the second book. The thing is there was a big hole to fill bc all those things that were supposed to be in the second movie are in the first. So it basically were a endless loop of fighting, getting back together, bla bla bla.

And I swear that in the books her choosing Peter makes a lot more sense. They actually show how they love each other and how much they matter to each other and in the end John isn't even close to what Peter is to Lara Jean.

They screwed the movies, but I swear the books are great.

snippet.textDisplay: The point of the second book was not "Team Peter vs. Team John" (which was a dumb marketing mechanism by Netflix to gain momentum for the movie) but the fact that LJ has never been in a relationship before and has to deal with fantasy vs. reality. Y'all be out here saying "John Ambrose is so much better than Peter" but don't act like y'all weren't rooting for Peter in the first book/movie. John is a fantasy. Just like how Peter was. The difference is that LJ is experiencing what it's like to date someone and deal with their past. We don't know what dating John is like, because he's a fantasy. For all we know, he could be hiding just as many ghosts as Peter. She hasn't seen him in forever -- we shall never know. But we do know that Peter is reality. Sure, he's done some shady stuff with Gen, but LJ has also done her fair share of shady stuff, keeping John a secret from Peter from the very beginning. And that's how a relationship sometimes is, especially your first one. It's not perfect. It's a lot of work. People will make mistakes. LJ had to learn that the hard way. Obvs, the movie doesn't do the book justice, and it never did. The first movie was mediocre at best with all the chicks strangely thirsty for Noah Centipoop's lack of a jawline and monotone voice. Netflix cut off every remotely significant and meaningful scene from the books to fit their agenda. LJ is also dressed like a 12 year old when she's supposed to like vintage things. I feel bad for Jenny Han. Read the books, people.

To be honest, I quite enjoyed this movie. I thought it was fun to watch Lara-jean interact with John Ambrose, I really liked John's character too. Yes, she did technically play those boys, but really I think it's understandable as to how everything moved the way it did. Sure some bits were unrealistic but still, I think that the movie was pretty good.


What I didn't like, however, was the lack of scenes with Peter and Laura-jean talking. Sure, they've had their scenes like dates and stuff but there were no scenes like the ones in the first movie, where the two could comfortable talk about to each other about their problems. In that matter, I was kind of disappointed since that's one of the features that I really like in their relationship within the first movie. :)

snippet.textDisplay: To be honest I could relate to this movie very well, and that is why I really liked it. To me it was realistic and it was comforting to know I wasn’t alone. I’m currently dating my ex bestfriend’s ex. And because she used to be my bestfriend, I knew everything they did, how they lost their virginity to each other, the places they went, the promises they made to each other. When he was my first in everything. I never thought these thoughts would hurt me until I experienced it myself. And yeah when things like that hurt you, often times you want to run away from it all, to somewhere or someone. However, what causes the sadness isn’t really those thoughts, but not understanding why you feel sad about it or why it bothers you and the thought of “why am I ruining my own happiness over something as small as this.” It’s confusing, tiring and draining.

snippet.textDisplay: I think she was more comfortable with John because he was a friend and there wasn't much extra personal baggage because he moved away. Even though they got on well and they had fun together, there wasn't much dimension to their relationship. Whereas with Peter, they had the whole experience of the previous movie. John's character is kind of bland but perfect whereas both Peter and Laura both had imperfections and made mistakes which I think makes it more realistic. Also I don't think Laura really actually liked John. I mean, she started thinking about it before she even met him after 6 years. Last time they met they were children. I think it was more the suggestion of someone else. I think John was there to contrast Peter's imperfections rather than be a stand alone character. To me, it makes a lot of sense that she chose Peter. It is like the teenage female equivalent of a man choosing to stay with his long term tired wife/ mother of his kids Vs a lively new woman who superficially seems perfect but would also be tired under the same circumstances as his wife.

snippet.textDisplay:
Do y’all not get that people come in and out of your life? she’s a young girl who hasn’t had a relationship.
She’s not use to having people that want her and when John came into her life, he was her first crush that had a crush back on her.
It’s like how you never truly get over your first love.
I’m pretty sure she wasn’t supposed to be seen as “the good girl that we should all love.”
She’s a confused teen who needed to see if she really wanted John or if it was just a feeling that would for sure go away.
That happens in real life, whether you like it or not i’m sure a shit ton of you have had slight feelings for someone else while being in a relationship.
Anyways stop hating on a decent kids/teens movie. It really wasn’t that bad.
